{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"81e4d433-14e8-43c5-bf80-b842b8dc0a49","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n### 1. `Directory.Build.props` at the solution root\n\nCreate (or merge into) a `Directory.Build.props` so all 3 projects pick up the same settings:\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n\n  <ItemGroup>\n    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.5.0\" />\n  </ItemGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n> If you have **non-test projects** in the same directory tree, move these into a `Directory.Build.props` scoped to your test projects folder, or guard with a condition in `Directory.Build.targets`:\n> ```xml\n> <PropertyGroup Condition=\"'$(IsTestProject)' == 'true'\">\n> ```\n> (use `.targets` for the condition since `IsTestProject` is set by the SDK, which imports after `.props`).\n\n### 2. No changes needed inside each `.csproj`\n\nThe three properties and the TRX package are inherited. You can remove any per-project `<IsPackable>false</IsPackable>` / test-runner boilerplate that's now redundant, but nothing else is required.\n\n### 3. CI command change\n\n```diff\n- dotnet test --logger trx\n+ dotnet test -- --report-trx\n```\n\nThe `--` separates `dotnet test` arguments from Microsoft.Testing.Platform arguments. `--report-trx` is provided by the `TrxReport` extension and writes `.trx` files to the `TestResults/` folder, same as before.\n\n### What each property does\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `EnableMSTestRunner` | Activates the MTP in-process runner shipped with MSTest 3.8 |\n| `OutputType Exe` | Required — each test project becomes a self-contained executable |\n| `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` | Lets `dotnet test` delegate to MTP instead of VSTest (needs SDK ≥ 8.0.400) |\n\n### Verify\n\n```bash\ndotnet test 